  "prompt": "What's the best book of Nietzsche's to start out with?",
  "response": "Starting with Friedrich Nietzsche's works can be quite an invigorating journey into philosophy, but the best place to start can depend on your current familiarity with philosophical concepts and your personal interests. Here are three popular recommendations for beginners:\n\n1. **\"Thus Spoke Zarathustra\"** \u2013 This is one of Nietzsche\u2019s most famous works and it beautifully encapsulates many of his key ideas through a blend of philosophical discourse and narrative style. It introduces concepts such as the \u00dcbermensch (Overman) and the eternal recurrence.\n\n2. **\"Beyond Good and Evil\"** \u2013 This work is often recommended for those new to Nietzsche as it provides a comprehensive overview of his philosophy in a more straightforward and systematic manner. It critically examines traditional moral philosophy and lays the groundwork for many of Nietzsche\u2019s ideas.\n\n3. **\"The Genealogy of Morals\"** \u2013 This book delves into the origins and development of our moral concepts, making it a fascinating read for those interested in understanding Nietzsche's critique of contemporary moral values.\n\nFor complete beginners, many might recommend **\"Thus Spoke Zarathustra\"** due to its unique and colorful style, despite it being arguably more challenging. If you prefer a slightly more structured approach, **\"Beyond Good and Evil\"** might be more suitable. \n\nIt\u2019s always a good idea to read some introductory material about Nietzsche's life and works to get some context before diving into his writings, as his style can be quite dense and provocative.",
